title: [Web] Inference speed halves if you open DevTools after loading an inference session, even if you close DevTools afterwards

labels.name: platform:web
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime web; typically submitted using template

body:
### Describe the issue

Opening and closing the browser DevTools/console significantly slows down inference times. Inference remains slow even after closing DevTools/console.

### To reproduce

Try visiting this in Chrome without opening the browser DevTools/console:

 * https://josephrocca.github.io/super-resolution-js/

Try using the example image and clicking "start" (after model has loaded) a few times to see the speed. Then open the console and it'll show you the inference times in the logs. Now close the console and click start a few times again. You'll see that inference speed has been roughly halved. Open the console to see inference times to confirm that.

The issue isn't specific to the above model. You can also do the same thing with this demo:

 * https://josephrocca.github.io/rwkv-v4-web/demo/

Click 'load' for one of the non-WebGL models (I haven't tested those) and then run the inference to see the speed. Open the console, and then close it again. Now run inference again and notice that inference speed is roughly half what it was before.


### Urgency

Not urgent. It's just confusing (especially since performance degradation persists even after closing DevTools) and may make developers thing that ONNX Runtime is worse than it actually is, e.g. when comparing to other libraries like tfjs/tflite.

### ONNX Runtime Installation

Released Package

### ONNX Runtime Version or Commit ID

1.14.0

### Execution Provider

WASM

### Describe the issue

I haved a pre-trained CNN model of tensorflow  saved model and I convert it to **.onnx form** as well as a **static quantized .onnx form**, and their inference latency at the same environment is respectively 7ms and 3ms. Then I tried to use Quantization-Aware training in tensorflow model optimization on the pre-trained model and then convert it to **quantized .tflite form**. According to QDQ format model instruction in the onnxruntime docs:

**ONNX quantization representation format**
There are two ways to represent quantized ONNX models:

- Operator-oriented (QOperator). All the quantized operators have their own ONNX definitions, like QLinearConv, MatMulInteger and etc.

- Tensor-oriented (QDQ; Quantize and DeQuantize). This format inserts DeQuantizeLinear(QuantizeLinear(tensor)) between the original operators to simulate the quantization and dequantization process. title: [CUDA] Fix FP16 Precision for Sigmoid Op
body:
Current Sigmoid's CUDA kernel uses target data type for all computation. For some small negative numbers, if using FP16, it will loss precision. For example, for input [-7.8477, 7.3320, -7.8008, 6.6016], the expected output is [3.9047e-04, 9.9935e-01, 4.0919e-04, 9.9864e-01], but current kernel will generate result [0.0000, 0.9990, 0.0000, 0.9990]. If some sub-graph contains Sigmoid, such as BinaryCrossEntropyWithLogits, it's likely to produce NaN as compute result.

The PR fixes this by using FP32 for kernel internal computation. Note that the fix will not have perf regression, as CUDA's _Exp will also do float to half casting, so the fix doesn't introduce extra cast. We move the cast to right begin and end of the whole kernel so that other parts of computation are also in FP32 (instead of only Exp).

### Description

title: STFT for DML EP
body:
### Description
Implements the STFT operator for the DirectML execution provider. This is implemented as a custom op, just like the DFT kernel, because it's implemented as a composite of two operators (DML Mul/Identity + DFT). As such, this inherits the same restrictions as the existing DFT kernel (requires power-of-two window sizes for now).

This change also adds a native FP16 shader to DFT so that both DFT/STFT kernels support float16 tensors. There is no typed UAV fallback or emulation path, so the HW _needs_ to support native float16. It also appears the stockham shader was compiled with all optimizations disabled and debug symbols (tsk tsk, Sheil), and this has been fixed.

This is passing all existing STFT tests (i.e. all of 1). I'm adding some additional collateral in the Windows AI conformance tests in parallel to check some extra cases.

body:
### Describe the issue

Related to issue #11348 this is the first case repro (why we have to use `CUDAExecutionprovider`).
PyTorch CPU does not support fp16, so we export with cuda. `CPUExecutionProvider` adds "cast" ops to the model that are necessary for `CUDAExecutionprovider` and are non-standard.

Before optimization
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/873905/220176604-f5f4f5fd-e9e8-445a-b5a2-d955a10fd62e.png)

After optimization
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/873905/220176665-72a92c30-c513-40db-a456-d26b54f13c5a.png)



### To reproduce

```python
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import onnxruntime as rt

class Repro1(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, dim=2):
        super().__init__()
        self.proj = nn.Linear(dim, dim)
    def forward(self, x):
        return self.proj(x)
    

m = Repro1().half().cuda()

data = torch.rand(32,2).half().cuda()
with torch.no_grad():
    out = m(data)


onnxfile = "/repos/output/repro1.onnx"
onnxfile_optimized =  onnxfile[:-5] + "_optimized.onnx"
targets = ["out"]
with torch.no_grad():
    torch.onnx.export(m, data, onnxfile,
                    verbose=True,
                    input_names=['data'],
                    dynamic_axes=None,
                    output_names=targets,
                    opset_version=14)

def optimize_graph(onnxfile, onnxfile_optimized=None, providers=None):
    if providers is None:
        providers = 'CUDAExecutionProvider'

    if not onnxfile_optimized:
        onnxfile_optimized = onnxfile[:-5] + "_optimized.onnx"  # ONNX optimizer is broken, using ORT to optimzie
    sess_options = rt.SessionOptions()
    sess_options.graph_optimization_level = rt.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_BASIC
    sess_options.optimized_model_filepath = onnxfile_optimized
    _ = rt.InferenceSession(onnxfile, sess_options, providers=[providers])
    return onnxfile_optimized

optimize_graph(onnxfile, providers="CPUExecutionProvider")
```
